04563nam a22007215i 9780292753709DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211984txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927537097 a10.7560/7757702doi  a(DE-B1597)588560  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPM3008b.L5 1984eb 7aLAN0000002bisacsh04a49722200aSupplement to the Handbook of Middle American Indians, Volume 2 :bLinguistics /ced. by Victoria Reifler Bricker, Munro S. Edmonson. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1984  a1 online resource (158 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tGeneral Editor's Preface -- tVolume Editor's Preface -- t1. Coatlán Mixe -- t2. Chichimeco Jonaz -- t3. Choltí Maya: A Sketch -- t4. Tarascan: From Meaning to Sound -- t5. A Sketch of San Luis Potosí Huastec -- tBibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe sixteen-volume Handbook of Middle American Indians, completed in 1976, has been acclaimed the world over as the single most valuable resource ever produced for those involved in the study of Mesoamerica. When it was determined in 1978 that the Handbook should be updated periodically, well-known cultural anthropologist Victoria Reifler Bricker was selected to be general editor. This second volume of the Supplement is devoted to Mesoamerican languages. It differs in both scope and content from its forerunner, Volume 5 of the Handbook of Middle American Indians: Linguistics, which presents a general survey of Middle American linguistics and descriptions of Classical Nahuatl, Yucatec, Quiche, Popoluca, Zapotec, Mazatec, Pame, and Chontal de Oaxaca. The aim of the present volume is to provide detailed sketches of five additional languages: Mixe, Chichimeco Jonaz, Choltí, Tarascan, and Huastec. All the grammatical sketches deal with the phonology, morphology, and syntax of the languages treated; most cover discourse as well. Taken together, these new essays represent a substantial enrichment of the earlier Handbook volume on linguistics. Alone, the Supplement stands as an invaluable reference guide for all who are interested in learning about these important and heretofore poorly treated languages of Middle America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aIndians of Central AmericazGuatemalaxLanguages. 0aIndians of MexicoxLanguages. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh1 aBricker, Victoria Reifler, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEdmonson, Munro S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdmonson, Munro S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFought, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedrich, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoogshagen, Searle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLastra de Suárez, Yolanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcQuown, Norman A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReifler Bricker, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/77577040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292753709423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292753709/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK